[Photos of NCD clinical signs (in chickens) are available at
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/diseases/notifiable/pictures/newcastled.htm>.
According to The Guardian, the infected avians were gray partridges; see
<http://www.guardian.co.uk/uklatest/story/0,,-6146837,00.html>. (Mary
Marshall is acknowledged for forwarding the above newswire).
Information on the vaccination history of the affected flock -- if
vaccinated at all -- would be helpful. According to Defra's information to
the OIE, prophylactic vaccination of poultry against NCD is undertaken
routinely in the UK. However, this might be different relating to game
birds. NCD vaccination of game birds is difficult and requires specialist
knowledge and experience. Gray partridges demonstrated a poor response to
vaccination with any of the vaccine strains used in a French trial; see
Guittet et al. Safety And efficacy of Newcastle disease vaccines in game
birds. In: Proceedings of the joint 2nd annual meeting of the National
Newcastle Disease And Avian Influenza Laboratories of countries of the
European Union, Brussels, 18-19 Oct 1994, pp 93-96, available at
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/proceedings1994.pdf>.

The following vaccines were used: Live vaccine strains Hitchner B1 (HB1)
and La Sota, administered by eye drop of one dose (0.03 ml) per bird; and
inactivated oil adjuvanted vaccine, administered by intramuscular injection
of one dose (0.3 ml) per bird. - Mod.AS]
